TAG CHALLENGE:

You can’t be a leader today unless you love people.

I said this to a room full of executives recently in an industry not known for being “loving”.

They initially responded with mixed emotions but when I asked them a follow-up question, their energy shifted immediately....

Have YOU ever worked for a leader that you just knew loved people? 

Almost every hand went up. 

And how did it make you feel? 

The answers were powerful.... 

Strong. Fearless. Seen. Cared For. Respected. Safe. Powerful. Brave. 

If the future is human-first, it’s going to take a different kind of leader to get us there and love is at the heart of it. 

Now of course we’re not talking about love in the romantic sense. I’m  talking about love as a force that activates creativity, purpose, meaning, and belonging. Love as the genesis. Love that activates the dormant potential within us and our people. 

WHO WAS THAT LEADER FOR YOU? 

Tag them below. Call em out.  Share some love.
Dropping in with one of the best in business. Nuggets to come.

The machines are coming, and we all know it.
 
The question is, will they augment or annihilate our professions?
 
For many of us it feels as if we’re playing a game of music chairs. It’s as if we can all sense the music is about to stop and we’re frantically looking for a spot to sit.
 
In world of ChatGPT and accelerating digital technologies, what role will we humans have to play? What unique value will we need to bring? What skills will guarantee us a chair when the music the stops.
 
If we want to have a place in the AI powered future of work, then we need to stop doing the work of a mediocre machines and start doing the work that only we as humans can do.
 
But how will we find the work that only we can do? What our human advantage?
 
To find it, we need to look within and draw upon our greatest asset, our strongest superpower.  The thing that makes us, us.
 
And nothing makes us, us more than love.
 
I mean really, is there anything more human than love?
 
After years of research, I think of love not only as the most powerful of human emotions but as an energetic force of creation. An act of nurturing expansion.
 
Thinking of love as an action instead of exclusively as a feeling is the first step in leveraging your humanity in the age of machines. In doing so we assume agency and accountability. Love becomes something we can do instead of only feel.

“Sometimes it’s takes you a long time to sound like yourself”

This is one of my favorite quotes from Miles Davis.

I’ve been speaking professionally for almost 15 years. For the majority of that time, I did my best to impersonate and emulate the best speakers of the day. Despite having some early success, I didn’t sound like myself yet. 

To make up for not having found my voice, I would often use my passion and enthusiasm in an attempt to overwhelm and persuade an audience. I’d use sheer energy to transform a room. And it worked. To an extent. I was good but not great. 

The hard truth was I didn’t trust myself. I didn’t trust that my insights were strong enough or original enough to stand on their own. I didn’t believe my own story was powerful enough to move an audience. 

I use to stand on chairs. I was all gas. 

And then COVID happened. 

Through the pain and challenge of delivering in an isolated virtual environment, I was forced to find a different gear. No longer were there chairs to stand on or stages to stomp around. I had to learn to develop my insights with more rigor so that they could be spoken softly and still be powerful. I learned how to excavate my own stories and share them vulnerably. 

And I started to understand that sometimes siting on a chair instead of standing on one can open up new possibilities for connection and transformation with an audience. 

Its 2023 and I’m starting to find my voice. I’m starting to sound like me. ❤️

If you’ve got a message inside but you haven’t found your voice yet, there is no better community in the world to help you not only find your voice but build, scale, grow your speaking business than @impact_eleven 

You belong in this community. 

#findingyourvoice

social_posts.post_text: Despite the ongoing demands for employees to return, the office as we know it is dead. The people have spoken. New rules for the new world of work.

Its not about doing what you love, it’s about finding the love in the work that you do. And when we tune into the work that energizes, inspires, and uplifts us, when we draw upon that force, we’re capable of creating services, products, experiences, and companies made with love. 

To be Made With Love signifies a creation infused with the passion, purpose, and heartfelt contribution of time, energy and emotion of its creator - resulting in products, services, experiences, that deeply resonate and move others…

In short, to be Made With Love is to leave a part of yourself in what you do. 

And here’s why that’s not just a nice idea, it’s the key to building better businesses and a better world. 

In our changing world of uncertainty and disruption, where so many of us feel isolated, lonely and disconnected, searching for meaning and purpose, I offer a simple yet profound truth: love, the deeply human energetic force of creation is the fuel for our expansion and growth, the guide for harnessing our passion and purpose and the secret ingredient to unlocking the ultimate competitive advantage. 
 
And I think as we move towards a future dominated by AI, and advanced automation, where commoditization will erase many of our traditional advantages, love stands as our indomitable, uniquely human edge. Our greatest asset to solve our biggest challenges and create a new future.

***New Program Alert

Yesterday was a celebration of months of hard work behind the scenes with a number of important people in my life, to bring a new message to world. In many ways it’s a love letter to the world. The reality is I’ve been working on this piece of thought leadership my entire life and yesterday I had the fortune to share it with an incredibly community of leaders from @csdadistricts - They leaned in, took notes, and shared from their hearts. And I’m so grateful we had the chance to share the morning together. 

At the heart of what we talked about was this idea that through out our history, when you stop to appreciate the most compelling and captivating brands, the most remarkable pieces of architecture, the most beautiful pieces of music, the most delicious meals, the most inspiring teams and leaders, etc, at their core, they all share the same thing. The thing that made them all so special, is that they were all made with love. In fact, I would say, everything great that was ever made, was made with love. 

But what does that mean to be “made with love”? 

In short, to make something with love is to leave a part of ourselves in the actions we take and the things we create. I think we all long to leave our fingerprints on things. We want to channel something real and we’re desperate to feel something real from the world. 

And as we move into an era dominated by AI, automation, and commoditization erases many of our traditional advantages as humans, love stands as our indomitable, uniquely human edge. 

It’s THE secret ingredient to building a better business and a better world. 

And we’re just getting started on this journey. The book is being written as we speak but I need your help. We need to share our collective stories of things made with love. From the biggest inventions to the pureness of small acts of heart-felt dedication to your craft, your stories matter and we need to hear about it!

As AI continues to commoditize and automate many of our competitive advantages, the strategy that wins the future for both individuals and organizations is making things with love because everything that isn’t made with love will be undervalued and ultimately forgotten.
 
Love is neither a luxury nor a weakness. Love is the strategy.
 
This matters more than ever as we look across industries and professions, our ability to create value is shifting towards the unique human aspects of our work that only we can do.
 
The job of the architect is no longer to draft blueprints, it’s to envision spaces that fuel human potential. The job of a programmer isn’t to write code, it’s to work with the business to identify where new value can be created. The job of the Financial Advisor is not to invest money, it’s to be there with care and compassion during life’s most stressful and difficult moments.
 
For all of us, the challenge isn’t merely to adapt but to deepen our commitment to infuse love and dedication into the facets of our work that only we can do.
 
Regardless of your profession, we must amplify those elements of our work that machines can never replicate. They may imitate tasks, but they can never capture the essence of the human spirit. They may replicate labor, but they can’t reproduce heart.
 
Find the soul in your role.
 
Let’s put love to work.
 
#MadeWithLove #HeartOverHardware #FutureofWork
Jobs are changing faster than people and we’re left wondering not just what work will be left for us but what will be left of us, in the work.
The Human Spirit is Strong

Your work might not be your identity but your spirit longs to contribute something of significance. 

You don’t have to change jobs, just your perspective. 

Make your work matter.
Heart over Hardware

In the quest to reach the zenith of our capabilities, it’s not the external challenges, but our internal dialogues that often hold the keys. 

Before we can fully show up for others, we must learn to first show up for ourselves. It’s tempting, especially as leaders, to push ourselves relentlessly—always striving for more. 

But here’s a paradox: To truly fuel our own performance, we must pivot. From being our own worst adversary to our most ardent advocate.

Tip 1: 🌟 Embrace Self-Awareness - Consistently reflect on the choices you’re making. Are they in line with your goals? If not, recalibrate. Your inner compass is more powerful than you think.

Tip 2: ❤️ Cultivate Self-Compassion - Mistakes happen. Instead of sinking in self-doubt, show yourself the same grace you’d offer a dear friend. Growth is a journey, not a destination.
Let’s lead with resilience and grace, turning criticism into constructive introspection. Remember, your biggest ally in leadership is the one staring back at you in the mirror.

Change your questions. Change your life. 

#Leadership #curiosity #influence

In today’s world, we face many challenges. Politics divide us. Misinformation confuses us. Social media overwhelms us. Yet, beneath it all, we seek truth. We want to connect. We want to feel alive. We want to know we matter. 

#leadership #putlovetowork

To do great work, you need do the work, with love. The reality is, many of us are not doing work we love yet. You might not be in your dream job but you can always put love into the work you do. This is your superpower and the path to work you love! 

#stevejobs #entrepreneurship #leadership #hiring #entrepreneur #hardwork #putlovetowork

Transforming Performance with a Thought! 🧠 

What if the key to unlocking potential in your people was a matter of expectation?  What if how you saw others, shaped how they saw themselves? 

This phenomenon is known as the Pygmalion Effect and was first discovered in a 1968 classroom experiment. 

The findings from the study have proven that the expectation of a leader has a direct impact on the performance of the person they are leading. 

Or as Rosenthal describes it, “What one person expects of another can come to serve as a self-fulfilling prophecy.” 

While the study was originally conducted within a classroom setting, it has since been accepted that the Pygmalion Effect applies to all kinds of settings from elite sports teams to the modern workplace.

Who helped YOU see more in YOURSELF? 

#BelieveToAchieve #PygmalionInAction

In a world swiftly adapting to AI, the real question is: What remains uniquely ours? The answer is simple yet profound: Our Love. - An energetic force of creation flowing through us. And our greatest advantage. 

As we move forward into a AI dominated world, every product or service not rooted in love will soon be lost in a sea of automation. Technology can replicate tasks, but can it replicate the human spirit. 

Go within. Your joy, passion, curiosity, and playfulness will guide the way to your gifts made with love to share with the world. 

So, where can you infuse love into your work? What needs your love to thrive? 

#FutureOfWork #EmbraceEmpathy #HumanEdge”#

Fear not, for this is our moment - and we’re in it together. 

For humans to thrive in this new era, we must re-imagine our role and the value we create by connecting to the parts of our work that only we can do. Because, while machines might replicate the work, they’ll never reflect the soul. They might take tasks, but they can’t take heart. It’s here, we find our edge.
 
Leveraging our human advantage isn’t just about helping to connect to more meaningful work. It’s about helping our businesses stand out in a sea of AI sameness. It’s about connecting with the market on a level that algorithms can’t. It’s about being so uniquely human that customers can’t help but pay attention and employees can’t help but love their work. 

Let’s unleash the power of people. Let’s Put Love to Work. 

#HumanAdvantage #HumanityFirst  #BusinessInnovation #madewithlove
